X being honored.

game.ts changes:
- type: Phaser.AUTO -> Phaser.WEBGL. Explicit WebGL pipeline pairs
  better with pixelArt + roundPixels and avoids the auto-fallback
  to Canvas on systems that have WebGL available but slow.
- dom.createContainer: false. No scene uses Phaser's DOM-element
  support in v0; all UI is canvas-drawn for crisp pixel rendering.
- physics.arcade.gravity wired to PHYSICS.gravityYPxPerSec2 from
  src/config/physics.ts (Principle III - no magic numbers in the
  bootstrap).
- callbacks.postBoot seeds the scene registry with
  devMode = import.meta.env.DEV. Scenes read this flag instead of
  importing import.meta in scattered places; production builds get
  devMode === false everywhere.

debug-overlay.ts (new src/systems/ module):
- attachFpsOverlay(scene): reads scene.registry.get("devMode") and
  early-returns when false, so production never pays the per-frame
  text update. When dev, creates a small monospace text in the
  top-left (depth = MAX_SAFE_INTEGER so it stays on top), refreshes
  every UI.fpsOverlayRefreshMs (250ms - smooth enough to read,
  cheap enough to ignore). Timer is owned by the scene so cleanup
  is automatic.
- No tests: depends on Phaser scene objects; unit-testing the
  rendering path would require jsdom + heavy mocking for negligible
  signal. The visual signal (you see FPS in dev, you don't in prod)
  is the test.

Supporting tweaks:
- src/config/ui.ts: fpsOverlayTopPx/LeftPx/FontSizePx/RefreshMs
  added under the "Dev FPS overlay" comment band. Principle III
  applied: even dev tuning is centralised.
- src/i18n/en.ts: "dev.fpsLabel" = "FPS". Even though this only
  appears in dev mode, the i18n seam is the rule. Costs three lines.
- src/scenes/BootScene.ts: calls attachFpsOverlay(this) at the end
  of create(). BootScene is the only visible scene during Phase 2;
  UIScene will inherit overlay ownership when it graduates from
  stub in T035 (Phase 3).

